The research presented here uses indicators (data) contained in the Local Data Bank, which is Poland's largest database of economic, social, and environmental data (
                        Local Data Bank, n.d.). The research was conducted based on a set of 19 indicators relating to the implementation of Goal 9 of Agenda 2030 at the regional level (Table 1
                     ). These indicators characterize the three areas of this Goal, namely innovation, industrialization and infrastructure. The indicators used for the study had to be statistically reliable, official and available, as well as complete for the entire period analyzed, i.e., 2015–2021. Filling the research gap in assessing the level of achievement of Sustainable Development Goal 9 at the regional level of one EU country applies to both time and objects (regions) under study. The study was carried out for 16 regions, corresponding to Poland's administrative and territorial division units, which are provinces (Fig. 1
                     ).

It seems that one way to support the regions may be to put more emphasis on the development of so-called Smart Specializations. The European Commission's initiative is designed to galvanize the regional scientific and research communities, local governments, entrepreneurs and others to build innovation in these regions. Many regions (provinces) have developed Regional Innovation Development Strategies, where smart specializations adequate to the region's capabilities and potential are identified (
                        Krajowa Strategia Rozwoju Regionalnego 2030, Warszawa 2019, n.d.; 
                        Regionalna Strategia Innowacji Województwa Małopolskiego 2030 (RSI WM 2030), n.d.; Inteligentne Śląskie, n.d.; 
                        Regionalna Strategia Innowacji Województwa Świętokrzyskiego 2030+, n.d.; 
                        Regionalna strategia innowacji województwa Lubelskiego do roku 2030+, n.d.). However, as some research (Asheim, 2019; Ghinoi et al., 2021; Barbero et al., 2022) indicates, the region's innovation development in terms of Smart Specializations must be based on the cooperation of industry and higher education, as well as on a developed network of sectoral or industry clusters. In such regions, it is necessary, as (Deng et al., 2023; Zhang et al., 2022; Aschenbrand, 2022; Yang et al., 2022) points out, to also undertake extensive measures including the promotion of local physical and social infrastructure, which can lead to an increase in the region's potential. This is why without a methodical approach to this issue, achieving success can be difficult. The process of improving regional innovation must involve all stakeholders in the process, including economic self-government in the form of Regional Chambers of Industry, as is the case in other countries.
